column27: Need but faster music to go with the ballet

column222: It was much nicer when you weren't having to focus on choosing a music piece

column22: I didn't feel that any of the 3 music files really harmonised with the artwork in my opinion
column32: I didn't really feel that any of the sounds represented the artwork at all, nor were they particularly pleasing to the ear.
column38: I did not like the drum sounds in relation to this artwork.
column48: Overall, I enjoyed the music except for the drums. I felt they didn't fit.
column54: I really enjoyed the Sound A music but didn't feel it matched the energy of the artwork. I felt the music had much more energy than the painting.

column22: While Sound A was the most pleasing, I think the heavy drums felt out of place in concert with the painting. Sounds C and D were really unpleasant to listen to because they were so off beat.
column38: Sound A would have made sense with the painting and been a better piece overall without the percussion which threw it off and seemed again too aggressive. Sound B was rhythmically all over the place and too fast-paced for the painting.  Sound D was the nicest to listen to and the one that felt most in tune with the painting - although, and this may just be personal preference, but the drums ruined it.
column54: Sound A felt most in tune with the painting, with the pacing. Sound B was too off beat to enjoy. Sound C was rhythmically unpleasant. Again the MIDI drums spoiled my enjoyment of all pieces.
column70: Sound A was a little disjointed but rhythmically suited the painting better. I thought Sound B was the most pleasant to listen to, although perhaps a little too fast for this painting. Sound C was too disjointed to enjoy.
column86: Both Sound A and B were slightly too fast for my perception of the painting although B was more enjoyable to listen to. Sound D was too disjointed to enjoy.
column102: Sounds A and B were both good but B was more pleasant to listen to and more accurately reflected the mood of the painting. Sound D was rhythmically and tonally unpleasant.
column123: Sound A was ok, but Sound C made more sense in terms of the rhythm and the dynamism of the painting. Sound D was an unpleasant sound and rhythmically bizarre.
column134: Sound A was very strange rhythmically and tonally. Sound B was a great match for the rhythm and brightness of the painting. Sound D, like A, was too disjointed.
column150: Sound A was pleasant to listen to and fit the rhythm of the painting - while the lower tones reflected some of the darker tones in the painting. Sound B and Sound D were disjointed.
column166: Sound D was too disjointed. Sound A was sonically quite boring. Sound C was reflective and felt more in tune with the painting.
column187: Sound A fit the painting - some of its more melancholy minor keys reflected the despondent elements of the image. So far I feel this has been the best match to any painting. Sound B was too offbeat and out of key to enjoy as was Sound C.
column198: Sound A was too offbeat to enjoy as was Sound D. Sound C was the best overall but still not a great fit.
